}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Danny Elfman]]\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Steve Bartek]]\n* [[Stewart Copeland]]\n* [[Steve Jablonsky]]\n}}\n| location                 = [[Universal Studios Hollywood]]<br/>{{small|([[San Fernando Valley]], [[Los Angeles County]], [[California]]) (filming)}}<br/>[[Wisteria Lane|Wisteria Lane, Fairview, Eagle State]] {{small|(setting)}}\n| num_seasons              = 8\n| editor                   = Karen Casta\u00f1eda\n| num_episodes             = 180\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Marc Cherry|Cherry Productions]]\n* [[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]]<br/>(2004\u20132007)<br/>(seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[ABC Studios]]<br/>(2007\u20132012)<br/>(seasons 4\u20138)\n}}\n| distributor              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n}}\n| list_episodes            = List of Desperate Housewives episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Marc Cherry\n* [[Desperate Housewives#Production crew|''See full list'']]\n}}\n\n| runtime                  = 43 minutes\n| related                  = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Devious Maids]]''\n[[Desperate Housewives#Adaptions|''List of adaptations'']]\n}}\n| website                  = \n}}\n\n'''''Desperate Housewives''''' is an American [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] [[comedy-drama]] television series created by [[Marc Cherry]] and produced by [[ABC Studios]] and [[Marc Cherry|Cherry Productions]]. It originally aired for eight seasons on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from October 3, 2004 until May 13, 2012. [[Executive producer]] Cherry served as [[showrunner]]. Other executive producers since the fourth season included [[Bob Daily]], [[George W. Perkins (television producer)|George W. Perkins]], [[John Pardee]], [[Joey Murphy]], [[David Grossman (director)|David Grossman]], and [[Larry Shaw (director)|Larry Shaw]].\n\nSet on [[Wisteria Lane]], a street in the fictional town of Fairview in the fictional Eagle State, ''Desperate Housewives'' follows the lives of a group of women as seen through the eyes of their friend and neighbor who took her life by suicide in the pilot episode. The storyline covers thirteen years of the women's lives over eight seasons, set between the years 2004\u20132008, and later 2013\u20132017 (the storyline includes a five-year jump in time, as well as flashbacks and flashforwards ranging from the 1980s to the 2020s). They work through domestic struggles and family life, while facing the secrets, crimes, and mysteries hidden behind the doors of their\u2014on the surface\u2014beautiful and seemingly perfect suburban neighborhood.\n\nThe series features an [[ensemble cast]], headed by [[Teri Hatcher]] as [[Susan Mayer]], [[Felicity Huffman]] as [[Lynette Scavo]], [[Marcia Cross]] as [[Bree Van de Kamp]], and [[Eva Longoria]] as [[Gabrielle Solis]]. [[Brenda Strong]] narrates the series as the late [[Mary Alice Young]], appearing sporadically in flashbacks or dream sequences.<ref>{{cite web|author=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/desperate-housewives/cast/ |title=Desperate Housewives Cast & Crew |publisher=TV.com |accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Desperate Housewives'' was well received by viewers and critics alike. It won multiple [[Primetime Emmy]], [[Golden Globe]] and [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s. From the [[2004\u201305 United States network television schedule|2004\u201305]] through the [[2008\u201309 United States network television schedule|2008\u201309]] television seasons, its first five seasons were rated amongst the top ten most-watched series.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.spottedratings.com/2010/07/war-of-18-49-desperate-housewives.html |title = The War of 18-49, Desperate Housewives}}</ref> In 2007, it was reported to be the most popular show in its demographic worldwide, with an audience of approximately 120 million<ref>{{cite news|title=Desperate Housewives On SABC3 Confirmed|url=http://www.tvsa.co.za/default.asp?blogname=news&articleID=4566|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=TVSA|date=April 3, 2007}}</ref> and was also reported as the third-most-watched television series in a study of ratings in twenty countries.<ref>{{cite news|title=CSI show 'most popular in world'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5231334.stm|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=July 31, 2006}}</ref> In 2012, it remained the most-watched comedy series internationally based on data from Eurodata TV Worldwide, which measured ratings across five continents; it has held this position since 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Most-Watched TV Show In The World Is 'CSI: Crime Scene Investigation'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/14/most-watched-tv-show-in-the-world-csi_n_1597968.html|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=June 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000446/2006 Monte-Carlo TV Festival (2006)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Moreover, it was the third-highest revenue-earning series for 2010, with $2.74 million per half an hour.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"American Idol\" king of TV advertising revenue|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/17/us-moneymakers-idUSTRE72G9FB20110317|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2011}}</ref> The show was ranked at number fifty-six on ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'s}} \"New TV Classics\" list.<ref>{{cite web|title=The New Classics: TV|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20207339,00.html|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=October 26, 2013|date=June 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, it was confirmed that ''Desperate Housewives'' would conclude after its eighth season; the [[Finishing the Hat (Desperate Housewives)|series finale]] aired on May 13, 2012.<ref name=\"tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com\">{{cite news|last=Seidman|first=Robert|title=ABC 2011\u201312 Primetime Schedule Announced|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/05/17/abc-2011-12-primetime-schedule-announced/92903/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=TV by the Numbers|date=May 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name=final>{{cite news|last=Finke|first=Nikki|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|title=EXCLUSIVE: ABC Will End 'Desperate Housewives' In May 2012 After 8th Season|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/08/exclusive-abc-will-end-desperate-housewives-in-may-2012-after-8th-season/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=August 5, 2011}}</ref><ref name=official>{{cite news|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|title=Desperate Housewives Boss on Cast's Reaction to Show Ending: 'There Was a Touch of Shock'|url=http://tvline.com/2011/08/07/abc-press-tour-desperate-housewives-ending/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[TVLine]]|date=August 7, 2011}}</ref> By the end of the series, it had surpassed ''[[Charmed]]'' as the [[List of longest-running television shows by category|longest-running hour-long television series featuring all-female leads]] by two episodes.\n\n==Premise==\n\nThe [[Desperate Housewives (season 1)|first season]] premiered on October 3, 2004, and introduces the four central characters of the show: [[Susan Mayer]], [[Lynette Scavo]], [[Bree Van de Kamp]] and [[Gabrielle Solis]], as well as their families and neighbors on [[Wisteria Lane]]. The main mystery of the season is the unexpected suicide of [[Mary Alice Young]], and the involvement of her husband [[Paul Young (Desperate Housewives)|Paul Young]] ([[Mark Moses]]) and their son [[Zach Young|Zach]] ([[Cody Kasch]]) in the events leading up to it. Susan fights [[Edie Britt]] ([[Nicollette Sheridan]]) for the affection of new neighbor [[Mike Delfino]] ([[James Denton]]), Lynette struggles to cope with her demanding children, Bree fights to save her marriage to [[Rex Van de Kamp]] ([[Steven Culp]]), and Gabrielle tries to prevent her husband [[Carlos Solis]] ([[Ricardo Antonio Chavira]]) from discovering that she is having an affair with their gardener, [[John Rowland (Desperate Housewives)|John Rowland]] ([[Jesse Metcalfe]]).\n\n[[File:WisteriaLanePurpleHouse.jpg|thumb|left|The Applewhite house, focus of ''Desperate Housewives''' season-long mystery from 2005 to 2006]]\n\nThe [[Desperate Housewives (season 2)|second season]] premiered on September 25, 2005, and its central mystery is that of new neighbor [[Betty Applewhite]] ([[Alfre Woodard]]), who moved onto Wisteria Lane in the middle of the night. She keeps some prisoner in her basement. Throughout the season, Bree tries to cope with being a widow, unknowingly begins dating the man who poisoned her husband, fights [[alcoholism]], and is unable to prevent the gap between her and her son [[Andrew Van de Kamp]] ([[Shawn Pyfrom]]) from growing to extremes. She deals with her daughter [[Danielle Van de Kamp|Danielle]]'s new romance with [[Matthew Applewhite]]. Susan's love life becomes even more complicated as her ex-husband [[Karl Mayer]] ([[Richard Burgi]]) is engaged to Edie and has also started to lean towards Susan. Lynette goes back to her career in advertising while her husband [[Tom Scavo]] ([[Doug Savant]]) becomes a stay-at-home father, and Gabrielle decides to be faithful to Carlos, and begins preparations to have a child. Paul is framed and sent to jail not for the murder he committed in the previous season, but for a fake one.\n\nThe [[Desperate Housewives (season 3)|third season]] premiered on September 24, 2006. In the third season, Bree marries [[Orson Hodge]] ([[Kyle MacLachlan]]), whose past and involvement with a recently discovered dead body becomes the main mystery of the season. Meanwhile, Lynette has to adjust to the arrival of Tom's previously unknown daughter and her mother to the family. The Scavos also experience tension as Tom wants to start a pizzeria. Gabrielle goes through a rough divorce, but finally finds new love in Fairview's new mayor. After being run over by Orson in the [[Remember (Desperate Housewives)|previous season finale]], Mike falls into a coma and suffers from amnesia when he wakes up. Edie sees her chance to make her move on Mike, and her family relations are explored throughout the season. Susan loses hope that Mike's memory will return and in the process moves on to a handsome Englishman whose wife is also in a coma, while her daughter [[Julie Mayer (Desperate Housewives)|Julie Mayer]] ([[Andrea Bowen]]) starts dating Edie's nephew. Elderly neighbor [[Karen McCluskey]] ([[Kathryn Joosten]]) hides something in her freezer. A shooting at the local grocery store leaves two characters dead and changes everyone's lives forever.\n\nThe [[Desperate Housewives (season 4)|fourth season]] premiered on September 30, 2007,<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC Announces Fall Premiere Dates|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?date=07/25/2007&id=20070725abc01|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=The Futon Critic|date=July 25, 2007}}</ref> and its main mystery revolves around new neighbor [[Katherine Mayfair]] ([[Dana Delany]]) and her family, who return to Wisteria Lane after twelve years away. Lynette battles [[cancer]]; the newlywed\u2014but unhappy\u2014Gabrielle starts an affair with her ex-husband Carlos; Susan and Mike enjoy life as a married couple and learn that they are expecting a child; Bree fakes a pregnancy and plans to raise her teenage daughter's illegitimate child as her own; and Edie schemes to hold on to her new love, Carlos. A gay couple from Chicago\u2014[[Lee McDermott]] ([[Kevin Rahm]]) and [[Bob Hunter (Desperate Housewives)|Bob Hunter]] ([[Tuc Watkins]])\u2014become residents of Wisteria Lane. A [[tornado]] threatens to destroy everything, and everyone, that the housewives hold dear. In the closing minute the characters and their story have flashed forward by five years.\n\n[[File:KathrynsHouse.JPG|thumb|The house of Katherine Mayfair on Wisteria Lane, as seen on ''Desperate Housewives'' from 2007 to 2010]]\n\nThe [[Desperate Housewives (season 5)|fifth season]] premiered on September 28, 2008, with the time period jumping five years after the previous season, with some flashbacks to events which happened between the two periods. The season mystery revolves around Edie's new husband, [[Dave Williams (Desperate Housewives)|Dave Williams]] ([[Neal McDonough]]), who is looking for revenge on someone on Wisteria Lane (later revealed to be Mike). Susan deals with being a single mother and having a new romance with her painter, while Mike starts dating Katherine. Lynette and Tom learn that their now teenage son is having an affair with a married woman whose husband's nightclub burns down with all of Wisteria Lane's neighbors inside. Gabrielle struggles with Carlos' blindness, two young daughters, and a financial crisis. Bree and Orson have marriage problems because Bree has become too focused on her career as a successful [[cookbook]] writer and caterer, while Orson was in prison her daughter came back for her son. Edie dies of electrocution after a car crash, before she can expose Dave moments after she discovers his secret.\n\nThe [[Desperate Housewives (season 6)|sixth season]] premiered on Sunday, September 27, 2009, at 9pm.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mitovich|first=Matt|title=ABC Announces Fall Premiere Dates for 19 Shows|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/FallTV-ABC-Premieres-1006734.aspx|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[TVGN|TV Guide]]|date=June 9, 2009}}</ref> The main mystery of this season is surrounding new neighbor [[Angie Bolen]] ([[Drea de Matteo]]) and her family. The first half of the season consists of Julie being strangled by an [[Karen McCluskey|unknown]] person, the conflict between Gabrielle and her niece [[Ana Solis]] ([[Maiara Walsh]]), Karen McCluskey finds new love. Lynette's attempt to sue her new boss Carlos, Katherine's eventual breakdown at losing Mike to Susan, and Bree's affair with Karl, which ends tragically when Karl's hired plane crashes into a building with the two of them and Orson inside. The second half of the season focuses on Katherine experimenting with her sexuality, Lynette inviting the Fairview strangler to stay with them before discovering the truth, the conflict between Bree and a son of Rex whom he had before meeting Bree, and the solving of the Bolen mystery.\n\nThe [[Desperate Housewives (season 7)|seventh season]] premiered on September 26, 2010,<ref>{{cite news|last=Seidman|first=Robert|title=ABC Announces Fall 2010 Series Premiere Dates|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2010/07/08/abc-announces-fall-series-premiere-dates/56502/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=TV by the Numbers|date=July 8, 2010}}</ref> and its main mystery is Paul's return to Wisteria Lane with a new wife and with plans of punishing the residents for shunning him during his incarceration, while an old nemesis of his still plans to get her own revenge on him. Lynette's best friend from college [[Renee Perry]] ([[Vanessa Williams]]) moves to the lane and stirs things up among the other housewives. Gabrielle and Carlos learn an unsettling fact about their daughter [[Juanita Solis (daughter)|Juanita Solis]] ([[Madison De La Garza]]) (who was switched at birth), which ultimately takes them back to Gabrielle's home town of Las Colinas. A now divorced Bree starts dating her contractor, and reveals the truth about the death of Carlos' mother, consequently ending the friendship between the Solis family and Bree. Due to financial problems, Susan and her family have moved off the lane, and Susan is forced to earn money by untraditional means. Following a major riot on the lane, Susan is put on the waiting list for a vital [[organ donation]]. Lynette persuades Tom to take an exciting new job, which leads to unprecedented problems in their marriage.\n\nThe [[Desperate Housewives (season 8)|eighth and final season]] premiered on Sunday, September 25, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nededog|first=Jethro|title='Desperate Housewives' Season 8 Premiere: The Ladies Keep a Killer Secret|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/desperate-housewives-season-8-premiere-240019|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 25, 2011}}</ref> The main mystery of the season is the death of Gabrielle's perverted stepfather [[List of Desperate Housewives characters#Alejandro Perez|Alejandro Perez]] ([[Tony Plana]]) at Carlos' hands, and its cover-up by the four housewives, which occurred in the [[Come on Over for Dinner|previous season finale]]. After the murder, Bree receives a blackmail letter from an unknown person similar to the one Mary Alice had received in the first season. Due to her relationship with detective [[Chuck Vance]] ([[Jonathan Cake]]), Bree becomes the main character affected by the cover-up of Alejandro's murder, and is eventually accused of killing Alejandro herself. A new neighbor, [[List of Desperate Housewives characters#Ben Faulkner|Ben Faulkner]] ([[Charles Mesure]]), moves into the lane, attracting Renee along the way. Ben is going through severe financial problems, and resorts to a dangerous and unruly loan shark to bail him out. Mike meddles in the business of Ben's loan shark in an attempt to protect Renee, but he pays the ultimate price. During the first half of the season, Susan struggles with the guilt of her involvement in the Alejandro case, and during the second half, she tries to deal with both Julie's unexpected pregnancy and Mike's death. Following the cover-up of Alejandro's murder, Carlos develops an alcohol problem, but Gabrielle persuades him to recover in rehab, which eventually results in Gabrielle and Carlos switching house roles. Tom moves out of the family home, and Lynette struggles to come to terms with how quickly Tom seems to have moved on, until she accepts that she is still in love with him, and decides she will try to win him back. Mrs. McCluskey receives worrying news about her health and decides to end it all, but Bree manages to convince her otherwise.\n\nThe two-hour series finale, which aired on Sunday, May 13, 2012, featured the conclusion of Bree's court case. To bring the series to a conclusion, there was a wedding, a birth, and a death, and the future of the four main housewives was revealed.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{See also|List of Desperate Housewives cast members|List of Desperate Housewives characters}}\nDuring its premiere season, the show featured thirteen starring actors, all credited in the [[Title sequence|opening sequence]]. For the show's second year, several actors, mainly [[child actor|child]] and [[teen actor|teenage]] ones, who had guest starred during the first season, were promoted to series regulars without having their names included in the opening sequence. Instead, they were billed as \"also starring\" during the first minutes of each episode, together with episode guest stars. This practice continued for the rest of the season.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14%;\" scope=\"col\"|Actor\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12%;\" scope=\"col\"|Character\n!colspan=\"8\"|Season\n|-\n!style=\"width:8%;\" scope=\"col\"|[[Desperate Housewives (season 1)|1]] \n!style=\"width:8%;\" scope=\"col\"|[[Desperate Housewives (season 2)|2]] \n!style=\"width:8%;\" scope=\"col\"|[[Desperate Housewives (season 3)|3]] \n!style=\"width:8%;\" scope=\"col\"|[[Desperate Housewives (season 4)|4]] \n!style=\"width:8%;\" scope=\"col\"|[[Desperate Housewives (season 5)|5]] \n!style=\"width:8%;\" scope=\"col\"|[[Desperate Housewives (season 6)|6]] \n!style=\"width:8%;\" scope=\"col\"|[[Desperate Housewives (season 7)|7]] \n!style=\"width:8%;\" scope=\"col\"|[[Desperate Housewives (season 8)|8]]\n|-\n|[[Teri Hatcher]]\n|[[Susan Mayer]]\n|colspan=\"8\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Felicity Huffman]]\n|[[Lynette Scavo]]\n|colspan=\"8\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Marcia Cross]]\n|[[Bree Van de Kamp]]\n|colspan=\"8\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Eva Longoria]]\n|[[Gabrielle Solis]]\n|colspan=\"8\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Nicollette Sheridan]]\n|[[Edie Britt]]\n|colspan=\"5\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|[[Steven Culp]]\n|[[Rex Van de Kamp]]\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n|{{nowrap|[[Ricardo Antonio Chavira]]}}\n|[[Carlos Solis]]\n|colspan=\"8\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Mark Moses]]\n|[[Paul Young (Desperate Housewives)|Paul Young]]\n|colspan=\"2\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n|[[Andrea Bowen]]\n|[[Julie Mayer (Desperate Housewives)|Julie Mayer]]\n|colspan=\"4\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#afeeee; text-align:center;\"| Also Starring \n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|-\n|[[Jesse Metcalfe]]\n|[[John Rowland (Desperate Housewives)|John Rowland]]\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"3\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|[[Cody Kasch]]\n|[[Zach Young (Desperate Housewives)|Zach Young]]\n|colspan=\"2\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|[[Brenda Strong]]\n|[[Mary Alice Young]]\n|colspan=\"8\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[James Denton]]\n|[[Mike Delfino]]\n|colspan=\"8\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Alfre Woodard]]\n|[[Betty Applewhite]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|[[Doug Savant]]\n|[[Tom Scavo]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"7\" {{yes2|Main}} \n|-\n|[[Richard Burgi]]\n|[[Karl Mayer]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n|[[Kyle MacLachlan]]\n|[[Orson Hodge]]\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"4\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n|[[Dana Delany]]\n|[[Katherine Mayfair]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|colspan=\"3\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n|[[Shawn Pyfrom]]\n| [[Andrew Van de Kamp]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#afeeee; text-align:center;\"| Also Starring\n| colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"3\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|-\n|[[Neal McDonough]]\n|[[Dave Williams (Desperate Housewives)|Dave Williams]]\n|colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|[[Drea de Matteo]]\n|[[Angie Bolen]]\n|colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|[[Maiara Walsh]]\n|[[Ana Solis]]\n|colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|[[Vanessa Williams]]\n|[[Renee Perry]]\n|colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|colspan=\"2\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Kathryn Joosten]]\n|[[Karen McCluskey]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#afeeee; text-align:center;\"| Also Starring\n| colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#afeeee; text-align:center;\"| Also Starring\n|-\n|[[Kevin Rahm]]\n|[[Lee McDermott]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"3\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#afeeee; text-align:center;\"| Also Starring\n|-\n|[[Tuc Watkins]]\n|[[Bob Hunter and Lee McDermott|Bob Hunter]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"3\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#afeeee; text-align:center;\"| Also Starring\n|-\n|[[Jonathan Cake]]\n|[[Chuck Vance]]\n|colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Charles Mesure]]\n|[[Ben Faulkner (Desperate Housewives)|Ben Faulkner]]\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"| \n| colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|-\n|[[Madison De La Garza]]\n|[[Juanita Solis (daughter)|Juanita Solis]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#afeeee; text-align:center;\"| Also Starring\n| colspan=\"1\" {{yes2|Main}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\nThe idea for the series was conceived as [[Marc Cherry]] and his mother were watching a news report on [[Andrea Yates]].<ref name=\"Bill Carter 2006, p. 161-162\">{{cite book|author=Carter, Bill |title=Desperate Networks|url=https://archive.org/details/desperatenetwork00cart |url-access=registration |location=New York|publisher= Doubleday|date=2006|pages= [https://archive.org/details/desperatenetwork00cart/page/161 161\u2013162]}}</ref> Prior to ''Desperate Housewives'', Cherry was best known for producing and writing episodes of [[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]]'s hit comedy series ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' and its successor, ''[[The Golden Palace]]''. In addition, he had created or co-created three sitcoms: ''[[The 5 Mrs. Buchanans]]'', ''[[The Crew (TV series)|The Crew]]'', and ''[[Some of My Best Friends]]'', none of which lasted longer than a year. Cherry had difficulty getting any [[television network]] interested in his new series; [[HBO]], [[CBS]], [[NBC]], [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]], [[Showtime (TV channel)|Showtime]], and [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] all turned the show down.<ref>{{cite news|last=McDougall|first=Charles|title=Desperately seeking a ratings hit|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/3634415/Desperately-seeking-a-ratings-hit.html|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=January 5, 2005}}</ref> Finally, two new executives at [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[Lloyd Braun]] and Susan Lyne, chose to greenlight it,<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC exec helps 'Desperate' network find its footing|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2006/02/22/tel_58689.shtml|accessdate=October 26, 2013|newspaper=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=February 22, 2006|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> reportedly after ''[[The O.C.]]'' on Fox premiered in 2003 and showed that a soap opera could succeed in prime time.<ref name=\"gopalan20130805\">{{cite web|last=Gopalan|first=Nisha|title=Josh Schwartz on The O.C., Casting George Lucas, and the Onslaught of Emo|url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/08/josh-schwartz-the-oc-anniversary-interview.html|work=Vulture|accessdate=September 20, 2013|date=August 5, 2013}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, Disney had both Braun and Lyne fired, following their approval of another new drama series: ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Olga|title=The man who discovered 'Lost' \u2013 and found himself out of a job|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1496199/The-man-who-discovered-Lost-and-found-himself-out-of-a-job.html|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=August 14, 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe ABC executives were not initially satisfied with the name of the new show, suggesting ''Wisteria Lane'' and ''The Secret Lives of Housewives'', instead.<ref>\"Desperate Housewives \u2013 The Complete First Season\" DVD</ref><ref name=\"Bill Carter 2006, p. 203\">{{cite book|author=Carter, Bill|title=Desperate Networks|url=https://archive.org/details/desperatenetwork00cart|url-access=registration|location=New York|publisher=Doubleday|date= 2006|page=[https://archive.org/details/desperatenetwork00cart/page/203 203]}}</ref> However, on October 23, 2003, ''Desperate Housewives'' was announced by ABC, presented as a primetime soap opera created by [[Charles Pratt Jr.]], of ''[[Melrose Place]]'' fame, and Marc Cherry, who declared the new show to be a mix of ''[[Knots Landing]]'' and ''[[American Beauty (1999 film)|American Beauty]]'' (1999) with a little bit of ''[[Twin Peaks]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Development Update: October 23|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=6211|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=The Futon Critic|date=October 23, 2003}}</ref> While Cherry continued his work on the show, Pratt was credited as executive producer for the pilot episode only, remaining linked to the show as a consulting producer during the first two seasons.\n\nOn May 18, 2004, ABC announced the 2004\u20132005 lineup, with ''Desperate Housewives'' in the Sunday at 9:00\u201310:00&nbsp;p.m. ET slot,<ref name=\"thefutoncritic.com\">{{cite news|title=2004 Broadcast Upfront Presentations: Abc, Part 1|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=6591|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=The Futon Critic|date=May 18, 2004}}</ref> which it held all through the run of the show. After only three episodes, on October 20, 2004, ABC announced that ''Desperate Housewives'', along with ''Lost'', had been picked up for a full season.<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC Orders Back Nine of Two Top-10 Series; 'Desperate Housewives' and 'Lost' Get Full Season Pick-Ups|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=20041020abc03|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=The Futon Critic|date=October 20, 2004}}</ref> A couple of weeks later after ''Housewives'' premiered the owners of NBC called to see who had passed on the series due to its ratings success.\n\n''Desperate Housewives'' was produced by creator Marc Cherry (Cherry Productions), Austin Bagley and, since 2007, ABC Studios. From 2004 to 2007, ''Desperate Housewives'' was produced in association with Touchstone Television.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n===Production crew===\nCherry, [[Tom Spezialy]], and [[Michael Edelstein]] served as [[executive producer]]s for show's the first two seasons. Spezialy, who also served as a staff writer, left his previous position as writer and executive producer for ''[[Dead Like Me]]'' to join the ''Desperate Housewives'' crew. He had also worked as writer and co-executive producer on several shows, among them ''[[Ed (TV series)|Ed]]'', ''[[Jack & Jill (TV series)|Jack and Jill]]'', and ''[[Parker Lewis Can't Lose]]'', while Edelstein had been the executive producer of ''[[Threat Matrix]]'' and ''[[Hope & Faith]]''.\n\nSecond season conflicts arose among the executive producers. Subsequently, Edelstein left the show mid-season, and by the season's end, so did Spezialy.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|last=Keck|first=William|title=Wisteria Lane's new landscape|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2006-05-18-housewives-main_x.htm|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=May 19, 2006}}</ref> For the third year, Cherry was joined by award-winning writer and producer [[Joe Keenan (writer)|Joe Keenan]]\u2014of ''[[Frasier]]'' fame\u2014and [[television film|television movie]] producer [[George W. Perkins (television producer)|George W. Perkins]], who had been a crew member of ''Desperate Housewives'' since the show's conception. Although receiving praise for his work on the show, Keenan chose to leave ''Desperate Housewives'' after one season to pursue other projects.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Michael|last2=Adalian|first2=Josef|title=Keenan not 'Desperate' any more|url=https://variety.com/2007/scene/news/keenan-not-desperate-any-more-1117962170/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 29, 2007}}</ref> Replacing him as executive producer for season 4 was [[Bob Daily]], who had joined the crew as a writer and co-executive producer during season 3. Daily's previous work include writing for the [[animated]] series ''[[Rugrats]]'', and for ''Frasier''. Also joining Cherry, Perkins, and Daily for season 4 were [[John Pardee]] and [[Joey Murphy]], who had been with the series since the beginning.<ref>{{cite news|title=Development Update: Week of June 11\u201315|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=7408|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=The Futon Critic|date=June 15, 2007}}</ref> Both had also worked on Cherry's previous show, ''The Crew'', in 1995, as well as on the sitcom ''[[Cybill]]''.\n\nIn the first four seasons, [[Larry Shaw (director)|Larry Shaw]] and [[David Grossman (director)|David Grossman]] have been the most prolific directors, together directing more than half of the episodes.\n\n===Filming===\n{{See also|Wisteria Lane|Colonial Street}}\n[[File:Beaver House 2003.jpg|thumb|left|The residence of Mary Alice Young (as seen in the premiere episode of ''Desperate Housewives''), on Wisteria Lane]]\n\n''Desperate Housewives'' was filmed on [[Panavision]] [[35mm movie film|35 mm]] cameras (except for the final season, which was shot digitally on the [[Arri Alexa]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Alexa meets Desperate Housewives|url=http://www.arri.com/news.html?article=901&cHash=1d726ec56efa76d0fee65c097ccc2a7e|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Arri Group}}</ref> It was broadcast in [[SDTV|standard]] and 16:9 [[widescreen]] [[high-definition television|high definition]], though it was framed for the 4:3 [[aspect ratio (image)|aspect ratio]]<ref name=\"asc\">{{cite journal|last=Feld|first=Rob|author2=Oppenheimer, Jean |author3=Stasukevich, Ian |date=March 2008|title=Tantalizing Television|url=http://www.theasc.com/ac_magazine/March2008/Television/page2.php|journal=American Cinematographer|volume=89|issue=3|format=}}</ref> until the final season.\n\nThe set for [[Wisteria Lane]], consisting mainly of facades but also of some actual houses, was located on the [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] back lot. It was referred to by film crews as ''[[Colonial Street]]'', and has been used for several motion pictures and television shows since the mid-1940s.<ref name=\"StreetHistory\">{{cite web|title=Colonial Street \u2013 History|url=http://www.thestudiotour.com/ush/backlot/street_colonial_history.shtml|work=The studiotour.com|publisher=Universal Studios Hollywood|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> Notable productions that were filmed here include: ''[[So Goes My Love]]'', ''[[Leave It to Beaver (film)|Leave it to Beaver]]'', ''[[The 'Burbs]]'', ''[[Providence (American TV series)|Providence]]'', ''[[Deep Impact (film)|Deep Impact]]'', ''[[Bedtime for Bonzo]]'', ''[[The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas (film)|The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas]]'', ''[[Gremlins]]'', ''[[The Munsters]]'', ''[[Psycho (1998 film)|Psycho]]'', ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', and the [[Doris Day]] comedies ''[[The Thrill of It All (film)|The Thrill of It All]]'' and ''[[Send Me No Flowers]]''.<ref name=\"StreetHistory\"/> For the second season of ''Desperate Housewives'', the street underwent some significant changes. Among the most noticeable of these changes was the removal of a church facade and a mansion in order to make room for Edie's house and a park.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colonial Street \u2013 Church|url=http://www.thestudiotour.com/ush/backlot/colonialstreet_church.php|work=The studiotour.com|publisher=Universal Studios Hollywood|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Colonial Street \u2013 Colonial Mansion|url=http://www.thestudiotour.com/ush/backlot/colonialstreet_mansion.php|work=The studiotour.com|publisher=Universal Studios Hollywood|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nInterior sets were built on sound stages at [[Universal Studios Hollywood]], some of which were duplicated in some form on the Wisteria Lane back lot for filming when conditions required it.<ref name=\"Wolf2013\">{{cite book|author=R. Craig Wolf|title=Scene Design and Stage Lighting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=roHj1fCd8m4C&pg=PA76|accessdate=July 11, 2013|date=March 26, 2013|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-111-34443-6|pages=76\u2013}}</ref>\n\nFilming for the series ended April 26, 2012.\n\n===Opening sequence===\nThe initial idea for the show's opening sequence was Cherry's. After asking 16 companies to come up with suggestions for how best to realize it, the producers finally hired [[Hollywood]]-based yU+co to provide the final version.<ref>{{cite news|title=yU + co Opens ABCs Desperate Housewives|url=http://www.digitalproducer.com/articles/viewarticle.jsp?id=29118|accessdate=October 10, 2013|newspaper=Digital Producer|date=November 12, 2004}}</ref> According to the yU+co's official website, the idea behind the sequence is, \"to evoke the show's quirky spirit and playful flouting of women's traditional role in society.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Desperate Houswives|url=http://www.yuco.com/projects/desperate-housewives|work=yU+co|accessdate=October 10, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026173402/http://www.yuco.com/projects/desperate-housewives|archivedate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> The images featured are taken from eight pieces of art, portraying domesticity and male\u2013female relations through the ages.<ref>{{cite web|last=Phelan|first=Joseph|title=Missing the Picture: Desperate Housewives Do Art History|url=http://www.artcyclopedia.com/feature-2005-05.html|work=[[ArtCyclopedia]]|accessdate=September 20, 2013|date=May 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe music for the opening was composed by [[Danny Elfman]], and has been awarded both a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] and the [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI TV Music Award]].<ref>{{cite news|title=BMI Film & Television Awards Tout Composers of Year's Top Film, Television, & Cable Music|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/bmi_film_television_awards_tout_composers_of_years_top_film_television_cabl|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=BMI|date=May 21, 2009}}</ref> In 2005, it was included on the album ''[[Music from and Inspired by Desperate Housewives]]''. When an episode runs long, only the first sequence (the falling apple) is kept. From the episode \"[[Now You Know (Desperate Housewives)|Now You Know]]\" onwards, a shortened synthesized version of the theme (arranged and performed by frequent series composer [[Steve Jablonsky]]) is heard, which underscores the falling apple scene, and the photograph of the four lead actresses, crediting [[Marc Cherry]] as creator.\n\n===Music===\nIn addition to the theme composed by Danny Elfman, the first two episodes scored by Elfman's assistant [[Steve Bartek]], and the third episode scored by ex-[[The Police|Police]] [[Stewart Copeland]], the series underscore music, composed by [[Steve Jablonsky]] since the fourth episode of the first season, defines the overall sound of the show by creating a musical counterpoint to the writing style. The score is electronic-based, but every [[sound recording and reproduction|scoring session]] incorporates a live string ensemble. Jablonsky incorporates recurring themes for events and characters into the score.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0558699/ \"Desperate Housewives\" Ah, But Underneath (2004)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Hollywood Records]] produced the first soundtrack album, ''[[Music from and Inspired by Desperate Housewives]]'' (2005), distributed by [[Universal Music Group]]. Several of those songs have been used in subsequent seasons.\n\n''Desperate Housewives''{{'}} unique style combined with the heavy dialogue and a quick-fire writing style limits the amount of [[popular music]] used within the series. The series' [[music supervisor]], [[David Sibley (music supervisor)|David Sibley]], works closely with the producers to integrate these musical needs into the show. In addition to featured performances by central characters such as Susan Mayer singing along with [[Rose Royce]]'s \"[[Car Wash (song)|Car Wash]]\" and Lynette's rendition of \"[[Boogie Shoes]]\", several characters have been accomplished musicians, such as Betty Applewhite (a concert [[pianist]]) and Dylan Mayfair (a [[child prodigy|prodigy]] [[cellist]]).\n\n===Later seasons===\nIn August 2009, Marc Cherry said that ''Desperate Housewives'' would be on television for a few more years, stating that the series still \"has a lot of life left in it.\" He told ''The Wrap'': {{quotation|Steve McPherson (ABC Entertainment president) and I agree that we shouldn't keep the show going for more than a couple [of] years past my seven-year initial contract. We don't want it to just fade away. We've been in negotiations. I expect to sign my new deal soon to set up a future scenario for the show. Someone else will run the show after season seven and I will serve as executive producer from a distance.}} He went on to explain that he felt the program had been revitalized by the five-year leap forward for season five, saying: \"Yes, I think it worked well. It was a way to start fresh and let everyone start from scratch in a way\".<ref name=years>{{cite news|last=Parks|first=Tim|title=Cherry: 'Housewives could be on for years'|url=http://www.digitalspy.com.au/ustv/s21/desperate-housewives/news/a173530/cherry-housewives-could-be-on-for-years.html|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Digital Spy|date=August 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, Cherry signed a two-year deal with ABC that could keep ''Desperate Housewives'' on the air until 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=Marc Cherry signs new deal with ABC|url=https://variety.com/2009/scene/news/marc-cherry-signs-new-deal-with-abc-1118010525/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Variety|date=October 28, 2009}}</ref>\nThe stars of ''Desperate Housewives'' finalized new deals to make way for the eighth season and signed at the price of $12 million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title='Desperate Housewives' Stars Finalizing New Deals, Paving Way To Season 8 Pickup|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/04/desperate-housewives-stars-finalizing-new-deals-paving-way-to-season-8-pickup/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Deadline.com|date=April 11, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Stahler|first=Kelsea|title='Desperate Housewives' Cast Signs on For Season 8|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/tv/7783436/desperate-housewives-cast-signs-on-for-season-8|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Hollywood.com|date=April 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McCathie|first=Lewis|title=Desperate Housewives stars net $12m|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/305633|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Digital Journal|date=April 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, Cherry hinted that ''Desperate Housewives'' would end in 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last=Wightman|first=Catriona|title='Desperate Housewives' exec plans 2013 end|url=http://www.digitalspy.com.au/ustv/s21/desperate-housewives/news/a302132/desperate-housewives-exec-plans-2013-end.html|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[Digital Spy]]|date=February 5, 2011}}</ref> and in April 2011, Eva Longoria confirmed that there would definitely be an eighth season and expressed hopes for a ninth.<ref>{{cite news|last=Still|first=Jennifer|title=Eva Longoria: 'Housewives finale amazing'|url=http://www.digitalspy.com.au/ustv/s21/desperate-housewives/news/a312988/eva-longoria-housewives-finale-amazing.html|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Digital Spy|date=April 6, 2011}}</ref> ''Desperate Housewives'' was officially renewed by ABC on May 17, 2011 for an [[Desperate Housewives (season 8)|eighth season]].<ref name=\"tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com\"/>\n\n===Final season===\nIn August 2011, it was confirmed that the eighth season of ''Desperate Housewives'' would be the final season.<ref name=final/><ref name=official/> Eva Longoria tweeted about the end of ''Desperate Housewives'': {{quotation|It's confirmed! We are filming our last season of ''Desperate Housewives''! I am so grateful for what the show has given me! We always knew we wanted to end on top and I thank ABC for giving us our victory lap! And a special thanks to Marc Cherry who forever changed my life!<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whosay.com/status/EvaLongoria/83265?code=iwKzky|title=Eva Longoria's post \"It's confirmed! We are filmin&nbsp;...\" on WhoSay|publisher=WhoSay|date=August 7, 2011|accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nCherry, the show's creator, made a cameo as a mover in the last scene of the final episode.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{See also|List of Desperate Housewives episodes}}\n\n<!-- Full linking is used in the following table so that it may be transcluded to the main series article -->\n<onlyinclude>{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |Season\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Episodes\n! colspan=\"2\" |Originally aired\n|-\n! First aired\n! Last aired\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#ff4848\" |\n| [[<includeonly>List of Desperate Housewives episodes</includeonly>#Season 1 (2004\u201305)|1]]\n| 23\n| {{Start date|2004|10|3}}\n| {{End date|2005|5|22}}\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#930000\" |\n| [[<includeonly>List of Desperate Housewives episodes</includeonly>#Season 2 (2005\u201306)|2]]\n| 24\n| style=\"padding: