ip-averages/94407 2010\u201311 Season Broadcast Primetime Show Viewership Averages], ''[[TV By the Numbers]]'', June 1, 2011</ref>\n|-\n!style=\"background:#F9F9F9;text-align:center\"|[[Desperate Housewives (Season 8)|8]]\n|23\n|style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>{{Start date|2011|9|25}}</center>\n|9.93<ref name=\"Season premiere DH\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/09/27/sunday-final-ratings-desperate-housewives-csimiami-the-simpsons-adjusted-up-60-minutes-adjusted-down/105018|title=Sunday Final Ratings: 'Desperate Housewives,' 'CSI: Miami,' 'The Simpsons' Adjusted Up; '60 Minutes' Adjusted Down|last=Gorman|first=Bill|date=September 27, 2011|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|accessdate=September 27, 2011}}</ref>\n|style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>{{Start date|2012|5|13}}</center>\n|11.12<ref name=\"8.22-23\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/15/sunday-final-ratings-once-upon-a-time-family-guy-survivor-adjusted-up-survivor-reunion-dateline-adjusted-down/134077|title=Sunday Final Ratings: 'Once Upon A Time', 'Family Guy', 'Survivor' Adjusted Up; 'Survivor: Reunion', 'Dateline' Adjusted Down|last=Bibel|first=Sara|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=May 15, 2012|accessdate=May 15, 2012}}</ref>\n|[[2011\u201312 United States network television schedule|2011\u201312]]\n|style=\"background:#ffdead;\"|#37<ref name=\"season8\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/24/complete-list-of-2011-12-season-tv-show-viewership-sunday-night-football-tops-followed-by-american-idol-ncis-dancing-with-the-stars/135785/|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=May 24, 2012|title=Complete List Of 2011\u201312 Season TV Show Viewership: 'Sunday Night Football' Tops, Followed By 'American Idol,' 'NCIS' & 'Dancing With The Stars'|first=Bill|last=Gorman}}</ref>\n|style=\"background:#ffdead;\"|2.74<ref name=\"Spotted Ratings\"/>\n|style=\"background:#ffdead;\"|10.60<ref name=season8/>\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n\nThe show was the biggest success of the 2004\u20132005 television season, being well received by both critics and viewers. The pilot episode had 21.3 million viewers making it the best new drama for the year, the highest-rated show of the week, and the best performance by a pilot for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], since ''[[Spin City]]'' in 1996.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jaffer|first=Murtz|title='Housewives' Premiere Cleans Up for ABC|url=http://insidepulse.com/2004/10/04/21768/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Inside Pulse|date=October 4, 2004}}</ref>\n\nAlong with ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'' and ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', ''Desperate Housewives'' was credited to have turned around ABC's declining fortunes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bianco|first=Robert|title=A good season, with reason|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2005-04-26-tv-lookback_x.htm|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=April 26, 2005}}</ref> Many critics agreed with Cherry's initial comparison to the popular [[black comedy]] film ''[[American Beauty (1999 film)|American Beauty]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Danger|first=Nick|title=TV Review: \"Desperate Housewives\"|url=http://blogcritics.org/tv-review-desperate-housewives/|work=[[Blogcritics]]|accessdate=October 10, 2013|date=October 4, 2004}}</ref> while its themes and appeal to female viewers were compared to those of the award-winning series ''[[Sex and the City]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=McFarland|first=Melanie|title=Timely 'Desperate Housewives' is life after 'Sex and the City'|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/tv/article/Timely-Desperate-Housewives-is-life-after-Sex-1155516.php|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|accessdate=September 20, 2013|date=September 30, 2004}}</ref> and its mysteries were said to resemble those of [[David Lynch]]'s classic series ''[[Twin Peaks]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schmeiser|first=Lisa|title=Fall '04: \"Desperate Housewives\"|url=http://www.teevee.org/2004/10/fall-04-desperate-housewives.html|work=TeeVee.org|accessdate=September 20, 2013|date=October 5, 2004}}</ref> In its first review, ''[[USA Today]]'' proclaimed the show to be \"refreshingly original, bracingly adult and thoroughly delightful\" and naming it to be \"sort of ''Knots Landing'' meets ''The Golden Girls'' by way of ''Twin Peaks''\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Bianco|first=Robert|title='Housewives' has the recipe for a bubbly evening soap|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2004-09-30-desperate-housewives_x.htm|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=September 30, 2004}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the initial success of the show, the term \"desperate housewives\" became a cultural phenomenon. This warranted \"real-life desperate housewives\" features in TV shows, including ''[[Dr. Phil (TV series)|The Dr. Phil Show]]'',<ref>[http://www.drphil.com/shows/show/425 Dr. Phil \u2013 The Real Lives of Desperate Housewives], Retrieved August 5, 2007</ref> and in magazines.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Real Desperate Housewives |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/the-real-desperate-housewives-1069770 |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=July 1, 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060519/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/the-real-desperate-housewives-1069770 |archivedate=September 21, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Blackwell |first=Elizabeth |title=Confessions of Real-Life Desperate Housewives |url=http://www.lhj.com/relationships/divorce/communication/confessions-of-real-life-desperate-housewives/ |work=[[Ladies' Home Journal]] |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053857/http://www.lhj.com/relationships/divorce/communication/confessions-of-real-life-desperate-housewives/ |archivedate=September 21, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Among the more prominent names to declare themselves fans of the show were [[Oprah Winfrey]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Brioux|first=Bill|title=Oprah pays a visit to 'Housewives'|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Television/TV_Shows/D/Desperate_Housewives/2005/02/02/917437.html|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=[[Canoe.ca]]|date=February 2, 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20050417062447/http://jam.canoe.ca/Television/TV_Shows/D/Desperate_Housewives/2005/02/02/917437.html|archivedate=April 17, 2005}}</ref> who also dedicated an episode of ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' to her visit at the film set; and the former [[First Lady of the United States]], [[Laura Bush]], who, in a comedic speech during a dinner with [[White House Correspondents' Association]] on April 30, 2005, stated, \"Ladies and gentlemen, I am a desperate housewife\", referring to the show.<ref>{{cite news|title=Laura Bush: First lady of comedy?|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-05-01-laura-bush-comments_x.htm|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=May 1, 2005}}</ref> The series ended up being the fourth-most-watched in the United States during the 2004\u20132005 season, with 23.7 million viewers each week.<ref>{{cite news|last=Grover|first=Ronald|last2=Fixmer|first2=Andy|title='Desperate Housewives' Hold Out for Pay Raise at ABC|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-13/-desperate-housewives-hold-out-for-pay-raise-in-drama-at-abc.html|accessdate=October 10, 2013|newspaper=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|date=January 14, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000937471 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 27, 2005 |title=Final audience and ratings figures |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051226102306/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000937471 |archivedate=December 26, 2005 }}</ref> The first-season finale was watched by 30.62 million American viewers becoming the most watched episode of the series.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Weekly Program Rankings |publisher=ABC Medianet |date=May 24, 2005 |url=http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052405_04 |accessdate=October 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217184619/http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052405_04 |archivedate=December 17, 2008  }}</ref>\n\nFor its second year, the show still maintained its ratings\u2014with 22.2 million viewers, it reclaimed its position as the number four most-watched series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002576393 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 26, 2006 |title=2005\u201306 primetime wrap |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060529003429/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002576393 |archivedate=May 29, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Bill|title=Mob Boss Takes Hit; Housewife Implicated|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/15/arts/television/15sopr.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 26, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 15, 2006}}</ref> The second season's premiere was watched by 28.4 million viewers.<ref name=\"premiereratings\">[http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=20050927abc02 Primetime Ratings for the Week of September 19\u201325, 2005], ''The Futon Critic'', September 27, 2005, Retrieved November 13, 2009</ref> The episode drew in the second largest audience for the series in its history. However, several critics started to notice a declining quality of the show's script,<ref>{{cite news|last=Guthrie |first=Marisa |title=In its second season, 'Desperate Housewives' is at a dead end |url=http://ecentral.my/news/story.asp?file=/2006/3/30/tvnradio/20060330091123&sec=tvnradio |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |newspaper=The Star Online |date=March 30, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053656/http://ecentral.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2006%2F3%2F30%2Ftvnradio%2F20060330091123&sec=tvnradio |archivedate=September 21, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Goldblatt|first=Henry|title=TV Review: Desperate Housewives (2004)|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1120827,00.html|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=September 20, 2013|date=October 21, 2005}}</ref> and ''[[USA Today]]''{{'s}} Robert Bianco suggested that the part of the series getting \"less good\" was that showrunner Cherry had left much of the series writing in the hands of others.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bianco|first=Robert|title='Housewives' is dragging desperately|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2005-10-09-housewives_x.htm|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=October 9, 2005}}</ref> Midway through the season executive producer Michael Edenstein left the show due to conflicts with Cherry and in May 2006, just a couple of weeks prior to the second-season finale, so did Tom Spezialy.<ref name=autogenerated1/> After the end of the season, Cherry agreed that the second year's script had been weaker and also agreed that it had been a mistake to let go too much of the show. He now stated that he was back full-time, claiming that both he and the writing staff had learned from their mistakes.<ref>Martin, Ed: [http://www.mediavillage.com/jmentr/2007/01/25/jmer-01-25-07/#continue Exclusive Interview! Desperate Housewives Creator Marc Cherry], ''Jack Myers Media Village'', January 25, 2007 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219225210/http://www.mediavillage.com/jmentr/2007/01/25/jmer-01-25-07/#continue |date=December 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.tvshows.nu/ABC-vows-stronger-third-season-for.html ABC vows stronger third season for its 'Desperate Housewives'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928222807/http://www.tvshows.nu/ABC-vows-stronger-third-season-for.html |date=September 28, 2007 }}, ''Wilmington Star'', July 26, 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20060718/desp_housewives_060718?s_name=&no_ads= Network exec promises better 'Housewives' season], ''CTVA.ca'', July 18, 2006 {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThe critics generally agreed on the improved quality for the third year,<ref>{{cite news|title=Report: ABC's 'Desperate Housewives' back on track for third season|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/report-abc-desperate-housewives-back-on-track-for-third-season-1009802.php|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Reality TV World|date=September 12, 2006}}</ref><ref>Martin, Ed: [http://www.mediavillage.com/jmentr/2006/09/14/jmer-09-14-06/ Sizzling Preview of Desperate Housewives] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061019005810/http://www.mediavillage.com/jmentr/2006/09/14/jmer-09-14-06/ |date=October 19, 2006 }}, ''Jack Myers Media Village'', September 14, 2006</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Taroli |first=Justin |title=The Third Time Isn't Always the Charm for TV Hits |url=http://departments.kings.edu/crown/articles/071116/tvshows.html |work=The Crown Online |publisher=King's College |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515220553/http://departments.kings.edu/crown/articles/071116/tvshows.html |archivedate=May 15, 2012 |df= }}</ref> but the overall ratings fell notably from previous seasons. Due to complications from her pregnancy, Marcia Cross was put on bed rest. After filming one episode from her own personal bedroom she was forced to take maternity leave with eight episodes of season three still remaining. It was predicted that the ratings would be down by over 25% since the premiere year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryan|first=Joal|title=Housewives' Most Desperate Hour|url=http://au.eonline.com/news/54858/housewives-most-desperate-hour|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=E! Online|date=April 10, 2007}}</ref> However, for the last three episodes of the season, the rating turned somewhat, and the season ended up with 17.5 million viewers, falling from number four to number ten on the list of most watched shows.<ref>{{cite news|title=2006\u201307 primetime wrap|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/2006-07-primetime-wrap-137223|accessdate=October 26, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 25, 2007}}</ref> While Cross' departure allowed for the much-underused Edie to have more story, fans noticed a decline in the stories during Cross' departure. Stories such as Lynette's emotional affair with restaurant manager Rick, proved unpopular. Furthermore, Susan's contrived triangle with Ian and Mike seemed tiresome to many viewers, particularly in an episode where Susan is lost in the woods. Notable, however, was that the show's rating among viewers age 18\u201324 increased from the previous season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vasquez|first=Diego|title=Fact: College kids now watch more TV|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/fact-college-kids-now-watch-more-tv/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Media Life Magazine|date=July 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\nFor its fourth season, the series proved to have staying power.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stack|first=Tim|title=TV Review: Desperate Housewives|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20156391,00.html|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=October 26, 2013|date=November 7, 2007}}</ref> The series averaged 18.2 million viewers. Ratings rose in the ninth episode \"[[Something's Coming (Desperate Housewives)|Something's Coming]]\", where 20.6 million viewers tuned in to see the heavily marketed tornado episode. The show once again moved back into the top five highest-rated programs in the 2007\u20132008 season, being the number-one ABC drama and beating popular medical drama ''Grey's Anatomy'' after falling behind it for the first time in the third season. It also became for the first time the number-one scripted series, beating ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]''.\n\nAlthough ratings were down for the fifth season, along with every scripted series on television, ''Desperate Housewives'' was still the most-watched scripted series on ABC, consistently beating the other ABC flagship shows, ''Lost'' and ''Grey's Anatomy,'' although the latter is still number one in the 18\u201349 demographic, followed by ''Desperate Housewives''.\n\nSimilar to the fifth season, ratings were down for the sixth season because of heavy competition in many airings, but the show still managed to remain the second most watched scripted show on ABC and the eleventh most watched scripted show of all broadcast television. The series continued to hit lower ratings, because of competition like the [[67th Golden Globe Awards]], [[52nd Annual Grammy Awards]], [[2010 Winter Olympics]], and the new [[CBS]] [[reality television]] series ''[[Undercover Boss]]''. Nevertheless, the sixth season managed to finish in the top twenty overall, both in total viewers and 18\u201349 demographic audiences. Among scripted shows, it still ranked in the top ten, in both categories.<ref>[http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2010/06/16/final-2009-10-broadcast-primetime-show-average-viewership/54336 Final 2009\u201310 Broadcast Primetime Show Average Viewership], ''TV By the Numbers'', June 16, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052710_13 |title=ABC's 2010 May Sweep and 2009\u201310 TV Season highlights |publisher=ABC Medianet |date=May 27, 2010 |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925075502/http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052710_13 |archivedate=September 25, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quotenmeter.de/cms/?p1=n&p2=43034&p3=|title=Die Season ist vorbei: Amerikas hei\u00dfeste Liste|publisher=quotenmeter.de |date=July 5, 2010 |accessdate=September 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2010/06/16/final-2009-10-broadcast-primetime-show-18-49-ratings/54330 Final 2009\u201310 Broadcast Primetime Show 18\u201349 Ratings], ''TV By the Numbers'', June 16, 2010</ref><ref>[http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2010/06/18/final-2009-10-broadcast-primetime-show-live7-dvr-ratings/54601 Final 2009\u201310 Broadcast Primetime Show Live+7 DVR Ratings], ''TV By the Numbers'', June 16, 2010</ref>\n\nThe seventh season premiered on September 26, 2010 and averaged 11.85 million viewers. The season saw new lows for the series reaching for the first time below 10 million viewers, and saw lows of 2.7 in the 18\u201349 demographic. For the first half of the season, ratings started strong averaging 12.3 million viewers and 3.9 in the 18\u201349 demographic which is similar to the second half of the sixth season. However, ratings declined in the second half of the season, after two contiguous episodes had to compete against the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]] and then the [[53rd Annual Grammy Awards]]. The show failed to recover to viewer levels hit in the first half of the season, and continued to receive 9\u201310 million viewers and 2.7\u20133.1 in the 18\u201349 demographic. This was the first time in its history that ''Desperate Housewives'' would not place in the twenty most watched shows of the season, although it would place in the twenty most-watched scripted shows.\n\nThe eighth season continued to see declines in the series' ratings. The season premiered to 9.93 million viewers and a 3.2 in the demo making it the least-watched season premiere in the series' history. The season began with ratings similar to those of the latter half of season 7, averaging 8\u20139 million viewers, and between a 2.8 to 3.0 in the 18\u201349 demographic. However, after the mid-season finale the ratings returned lower, hitting the seven million viewer mark and a 2.2\u20132.5 in the demo. The season also saw the lowest ratings in the show's eight-year run. Opposite the [[54th Annual Grammy Awards]], which featured a tribute to the then-recently deceased entertainer [[Whitney Houston]], and the mid-season premiere of ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'' on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]], the show fell to a 1.8 rating in adults 18\u201349 and 6.4 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gorman |first=Bill |title=TV Ratings Sunday: Whitney Houston Memories Rocket 'Grammy Awards' Ratings, Pushes Competition To Lows |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/02/13/tv-ratings-sunday-whitney-houston-memories-rocket-grammy-awards-ratings/119540/ |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |newspaper=TV by the Numbers |date=February 13, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054242/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/02/13/tv-ratings-sunday-whitney-houston-memories-rocket-grammy-awards-ratings/119540/ |archivedate=September 21, 2013  }}</ref> However unlike the seventh season, the show's ratings slightly recovered after the series low and leveled around the eight million viewer mark and a 2.6 in the demo. Despite the series lows, the season finale was able to go out on a season high in the ratings and the highest rated episode in over a year and a half, since March 2011 with \"[[Searching (Desperate Housewives)|Searching]]\". The series finale titled \"[[Finishing the Hat (Desperate Housewives)|Finishing the Hat]]\" aired May 13, 2012 was viewed by 11.12 million viewers and a 3.2 in the demo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/15/sunday-final-ratings-once-upon-a-time-family-guy-survivor-adjusted-up-survivor-reunion-dateline-adjusted-down/134077/|title=Sunday Final Ratings: 'Once Upon A Time', 'Family Guy', 'Survivor' Adjusted Up; 'Survivor: Reunion', 'Dateline' Adjusted Down|publisher=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> Despite the lows in the ratings the show managed to remain in the top twenty-five-watched shows in the 18\u201349 demographic, placing at number twenty-five. However, the show dropped out of the top thirty most-watched shows in total viewers, coming in at thirty-fifth place.<ref name=\"deadline.com\">{{cite news|last=Gorman|first=Bill|title=Complete List Of 2011\u201312 Season TV Show Viewership: 'Sunday Night Football' Tops, Followed By 'American Idol,' 'NCIS' & 'Dancing With The Stars'|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/24/complete-list-of-2011-12-season-tv-show-viewership-sunday-night-football-tops-followed-by-american-idol-ncis-dancing-with-the-stars/135785/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=TV by the Numbers|date=May 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the American cable network [[Bravo (U.S. TV channel)|Bravo]] launched their [[reality television|reality series]], ''[[The Real Housewives of...]]'', in the footsteps of the \"real life desperate housewives\" phenomenon.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chang|first=Richard|title=TV: \"The Real Housewives of Orange County\"|url=http://www.ocregister.com/entertainment/-118440--.html|work=[[The Orange County Register]]|accessdate=October 26, 2013|date=March 12, 2006}}</ref> That program has taken place in areas such as [[Orange County, California|Orange County (California)]], [[Atlanta]], and two series within the New York-[[Tri-State Region]], within the City itself and the [[New Jersey]] suburbs. According to a survey of twenty countries conducted in 2006 by ''Informa Telecoms and Media'', ''Desperate Housewives'' was the third-most-watched television series in the world, after fellow American series ''[[CSI: Miami]]'' and ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5231334.stm|date=July 31, 2006|title=CSI show 'most popular in world'|publisher=BBC}}</ref> During a fundraising auction for the British child charity [[ChildLine]] in December 2006, a walk-on part in ''Desperate Housewives'' had the highest bid, \u00a317,000, beating [[Daniel Craig]]'s [[James Bond]] tuxedo from ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond tuxedo raises \u00a312,000|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6168389.stm|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=December 11, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond, 'Desperate Housewives' Raise Money for UK Charity |url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2006/12/11/james_bond_desperate_housewives_raise_mo |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |newspaper=Starpulse.com |date=December 11, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060531/http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2006/12/11/james_bond_desperate_housewives_raise_mo |archivedate=September 21, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn its first public release of online individual television program rankings, [[Nielsen Media Research]] announced that the series had 723,000 unique online viewers in December 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Lost\" Is Found By Online Viewers|url=http://www.nielsen.com/us/en/newswire/2009/lost-is-found-by-online-viewers.html|accessdate=October 22, 2013|newspaper=Neilsen|date=February 22, 2009}}</ref> ''Desperate Housewives'' was the seventh-most-pirated television show of 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bierly|first=Mandi|title=Most pirated shows of 2009: Someone's still watching 'Heroes'|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/01/05/pirated-tv-shows-2009/|accessdate=September 20, 2013|newspaper=Entertainment Weekly|date=January 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn fall 2013, North Korea allegedly executed eighty people for watching banned South Korean soap operas, ''Desperate Housewives'' being the most common soap opera. ''Desperate Housewives'' was being secretly watched using [[mp3 players]], [[hard drives]], and [[DVD-Video|DVDs]].<ref>[https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/11/13/nork_soap_opera_executions/ The Register]</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, ''Desperate Housewives'' ranked at number hundred on ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''{{'}}s \"Hollywood's 100 Favorite TV Shows\", as determined by television industry professionals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hollywood's 100 Favorite TV Shows|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/best-tv-shows-ever-top-819499/item/desperate-housewives-hollywoods-100-favorite-820451|accessdate=September 20, 2015|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Desperate Housewives}}\n\n[[Image:Desperate Housewives at 2008 GLAAD Awards.jpg|L\u2013R: [[Dana Delany]], [[Teri Hatcher]], [[Brenda Strong]] and [[Andrea Bowen]] at the [[20th GLAAD Media Awards]] at the [[Nokia Theatre L.A. Live|Nokia Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] on April 18, 2009|thumb|right]]\nFor its premiere season, the show was awarded six [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, two [[Golden Globe Awards]] and two [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s. The nominations of all of the leading actresses except [[Eva Longoria]] for both the Golden Globe Award and Primetime Emmy Award received some media interest. While Longoria seemingly wasn't bothered, stating for the press that \"I'm new. I just arrived. I didn't expect at all to be in the minds of the Academy\", Marc Cherry regarded them being left out as a \"horrendous error\".<ref>[http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/longoria%20i%20never%20expected%20an%20emmy Longoria: \"I Never Expected an Emmy\"], ''ContactMusic.com'', July 24, 2005</ref> In the end, the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]] went to [[Felicity Huffman]], while [[Teri Hatcher]] won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress - Musical or Comedy Series|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Musical or Comedy]], as well as the Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Actress \u2013 Comedy Series.\n\nThe show's second Golden Globe Award for its first year was for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Series - Musical or Comedy|Best Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] at the [[62nd Golden Globe Awards]], while the other Primetime Emmy Awards went to [[Kathryn Joosten]], for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series]], for her guest role as Karen McCluskey (beating, among others, fellow cast member [[Lupe Ontiveros]]); to [[Charles McDougall]], for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]], for his direction of \"Pilot\"; to [[Danny Elfman]], for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music|Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]], for his theme music; for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Single-Camera Picture Editing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Single-Camera Picture Editing for a Comedy Series]] of \"Pilot\"; and for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Casting for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Casting for a Comedy Series]] at the [[57th Annual Primetime Emmy Awards]]. The entire cast was awarded the Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Cast \u2013 Comedy Series (in both 2004 and 2005), and [[Nicollette Sheridan]] was nominated for the Golden Globe Award for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress - Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]].\n\nIn 2006, the show continued to receive several nominations. It was awarded with yet another Golden Globe Award for Best Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy at the [[63rd Golden Globe Awards]], and all the four leading women received Golden Globe Award nominations, although none of them won. The cast ensemble was awarded with another Screen Actors Guild Award, as was Felicity Huffman. Primetime Emmy Award nominations at the [[58th Primetime Emmy Awards]] included, among others, guest actress [[Shirley Knight]] and supporting actress [[Alfre Woodard]], although none of them resulted in a win. It was nominated for the Pioneer Award at the [[BAFTA]] awards but lost to ''[[Doctor Who]]'', which at the time was recently revamped.\n\nThe show did continue to be nominated in 2007\u2014Felicity Huffman was granted a Primetime Emmy Award nomination for the second time, and guest actresses [[Laurie Metcalf]] and [[Dixie Carter]] also received Primetime Emmy Award nominations, at the [[59th Primetime Emmy Awards]]. The show, along with actresses Marcia Cross and Felicity Huffman, received Golden Globe Award nominations at [[64th Golden Globe Awards]], and Huffman and the cast ensemble were also nominated for the Screen Actors Guild Awards. None of the Primetime Emmy Award, Golden Globe Award, or Screen Actors Guild Award nominations resulted in any actual awards.\n\n2008 yielded the least nominations with none at the [[65th Golden Globe Awards]] and only the cast being nominated at the Screen Actors Guild Awards. The show was nominated for four Primetime Emmy Awards at the [[60th Primetime Emmy Awards]], including acting nods towards [[Polly Bergen]] and [[Kathryn Joosten]] for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series. Joosten won the show's seventh Primetime Emmy Award and first since its debut year.\n\nNominations continued to decline in later years. Notable nominations included nods towards [[Beau Bridges]] and [[Kathryn Joosten]] in 2009 and 2010, respectively. Additionally, [[Brenda Strong]] received her first Primetime Emmy Award nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Voice-Over Performance|Outstanding Voice-Over Performance]] at the [[63rd Primetime Emmy Awards]] in 2011, a notable feat for a category usually dominated by animated series. Also in 2011, Vanessa L. Williams won a [[NAACP Image Award]] for [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] at the [[41st NAACP Image Awards]] and a [[Satellite Award]] for Best Actress in a Supporting Role in a Series, Mini-Series or Motion Picture Made for Television. Strong and Joosten received Primetime Emmy Award nominations again at [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards]] in 2012 and Williams won a [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]] for the series' eight and final season in 2013.\n\nOther notable awards include the [[People's Choice Award]] for Favorite New Television Drama at the [[31st People's Choice Awards]], the Future Classic Award at the 2005 [[TV Land Award]]s, the TP de Oro for Best Foreign Series in 2006, and seven [[Golden Nymph Award]]s at [[Monte-Carlo Television Festival]]s, among others.<ref>[http://imdb.com/title/tt0410975/awards The IMDb.com list of awards for Desperate Housewives], Retrieved August 3, 2007</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThere have only been [[DVD-Video|DVD]] releases of the show. No [[High-definition video|HD]] or [[Blu-ray]] version has been released on disc as of 2019.\n\n{{Main|List of Desperate Housewives home video releases}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Region 1\n! scope=\"col\"| Region 2\n! scope=\"col\"| {{nowrap|Region 3}}\n! scope=\"col\"| Region 4\n! scope=\"col\"| {{nowrap|Region 5}}\n! scope=\"col\"| No. of discs\n! scope=\"col\"| No. of episodes\n! scope=\"col\"| Ref.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=\"center\"| The Complete First Season\n| align=\"center\"| September 20, 2005\n| align=\"center\"| October 10, 2005\n| align=\"center\"| November 16, 2005\n| align=\"center\"| November 28, 2005\n| align=\"center\"| July 18, 2006\n| align=\"center\"| {{flatlist|\n* 6\n* 5<br/>{{small|(Region 5)}}\n}}\n| align=\"center\"| 23\n| align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Desperate-Housewives-Season-1-DVD/dp/B0009FZGTG|title=Desperate Housewives: Season 1 [DVD]: Amazon.co.uk: Teri Hatcher and 1 more|publisher=[[Amazon.co.uk]]|date=2005|accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yesasia.com/global/desperate-housewives-season-1-vol-1-23-end-hong-kong-version/1004094708-0-0-0-en/info.html|title=YESASIA: Desperate Housewives (Season 1) (Vol.1\u201323) (End) (Hong Kong Version)|publisher=[[YesAsia]]|date=November 16, 2005|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align